@node Requirements " Requirements "


                            ****************
                              Requirements
                            ****************

 AppInfo was compiled with SAS/C-compiler v6.5 on an Amiga 500
 Kickstart V37.175, Workbench V38.35 with 4MB memory + 80MB harddisk.

 Hopefully it'll work on any Amiga as long as it has Kickstart 37++, but if
 it doesn't, please @{"let me know" link BugReports}.

@endnode
@node Introduction " Introduction "


                            ****************
                              Introduction
                            ****************

 The Workbench have become more and more powerfull since OS 2.04, but there
 are still a few things you have to do from CLI.

 One of these things is finding out the bytesize of a file or drawer.
 Another is finding out the versionnumber of a file.

 This is what AppInfo will do for you.

 When you start AppInfo, an appicon will popup on the Workbench window
 (you can set position, image and title).

 If you drop only one file on the appicon, AppInfo will show you the path,
 the size in bytes and blocks and the versionstring (if one was found).

 If you drop several files/drawers/disks on the appicon, AppInfo will show
 you the total number of files, drawers, bytes and blocks.

 No versionstring will be shown when more than one file is droped. I thought
 this was better then having to OK all requesters if you drop many files.

 In case you for some reason want to quit, you can doubleclick on the appicon
 This will open a requester showing some information about the program.
 From here you may either choose Continue or Quit.

 NOTE! Droping an icon that has no file will open the requester. This is not
 a bug but a "sideeffect" of the Workbench message handling.

 AppInfo can also take a path/filename at startup.
 To do this from CLI you just add the paths/files you want to include.
 From Workbench you first click on the AppInfo icon then click on the
 paths/files you want, remember to hold down SHIFT while clicking on
 the icons.

 NOTE! When AppInfo is given a file/path at startup, no appicon will be
 added.

@endnode
@node Options " Commandline options "

 Here are the valid arguments/tooltypes for AppInfo.

  AppInfo PATH/M,ICON/K,TITLE/K,XPOS/N,YPOS/N


   PATH    - (optional from CLI only)
             By adding one or more paths/filenames, AppInfo will examine
             these and not open any appicon. This can be usefull from
             ex. DirOpus.

             NOTE! Path is NOT a tooltype.

   ICON    - (optional)
             By adding this keyword followed by the name of an icon,
             AppInfo will use this icon instead of its own.
             The prefix '.info' is optional.

   TITLE   - (optional)
             By adding this keyword followed by a string, AppInfo will
             use this string as the title instead of 'AppInfo'.
             Remember to put the string within quotes (") if it contain
             spaces.

   XPOS    - (optional)
             With this keyword, you can set the x-coordinate (in pixels)
             where the icon will appear.

   YPOS    - (optional)
             With this keyword, you can set the y-coordinate (in pixels)
             where the icon will appear.

   If no position is given, the icon will appear at a free space.

   If you put AppInfo in WBStartup you may want to add the DONOTWAIT-
   tooltype to avoid anoying requesters at startup.
@endnode
@node VersionNotes " AppInfo version notes "

 Version          Changes
 =======          =======

  1.0             First release.

  1.1             Droping a textfile containing a versionstring would cause
                  a giant requester followed by a guru. This has been fixed.

  1.2             AppInfo now takes a path/filename as an argument and use
                  this instead of opening an appicon. If no path/filename
                  is given, AppInfo will open an appicon.
                  Optimized the versionstring seek routine. It is now 600%
                  faster.
                  AppInfo now shows the true block-size (including header).
@endnode
